            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the projector\u2019s hum in the conference room a decade ago. On the screen, the line item for his supportive housing pilot\u2014months of his life, his earnest belief made manifest in data\u2014was highlighted. Then, with a dispassionate click, it was deleted. Replaced by funding for a splashier initiative. It wasn't anger he felt, but a cold hollowing out. In that moment, his idealism didn't die; it hardened into a resolve. Passion was a currency with no value here. He would learn to speak the only language that mattered: the budget.\n\n***\n\n2.\nOne evening, about six years ago, Clara had unrolled a set of architectural blueprints across their dining table. While she spoke of sightlines and aesthetic flow, Adam found himself tracing the plumbing and electrical schematics. He asked about material tensile strength and compliance with Title 24. She smiled, a look of deep recognition in her eyes. It was the first time he felt his love for systems was not just a professional asset, but something intimate and understood\u2014a shared language between them that was as structural as it was romantic.\n\n***\n\n3.\nFresh out of Davis and new to the city, he stood transfixed before a giant Muni map at a bus shelter. Others saw destinations; he saw a sprawling, color-coded circulatory system. He noted the intersecting lines, the transfer points, the service gaps in certain neighborhoods. It was the most beautiful, complex puzzle he had ever seen. The tourist romance of cable cars and bridges held no appeal, but this map\u2014this intricate schematic of human movement and civic planning\u2014was the moment he truly fell for San Francisco\u2019s challenge.\n\n***\n\n4.\nWalking home through the Tenderloin a few years back, he saw them: a half-dozen new, tamper-proof needle disposal boxes. A tiny, unglamorous project he\u2019d championed. He had found the surplus funds in a parks department landscaping budget and painstakingly rerouted them. No one would ever know his name was attached to it. But seeing one in use, a small act of public health and dignity made possible by a line on his spreadsheet, brought a surge of quiet, fierce satisfaction. This was what power, properly wielded, could do.\n\n***\n\n5.\nJust last month, he paused on his walk home from the Muni stop in Hayes Valley. He was looking at the new ADA-compliant curb ramps at the corner, their gentle slope and bright yellow textured warnings gleaming under the streetlights. He knew to the dollar what they cost. He knew the department, the funding source, and the public works order number. To anyone else, it was just a sidewalk. To Adam, it was a small piece of his legacy written in concrete: a permanent, functional improvement, perfectly balanced and accounted for."
